quizzes.question:
Create a general for loop:
[!raw!]
for ({0}; {1}; {2})
{
  Console.WriteLine(x);
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The for Loop[/h1]

A [b]for [/b]loop executes a set of statements a specific number of times, and has the syntax:[code format="cs" ][b]for [/b]( [b]init[/b]; [b]condition[/b]; [b]increment [/b]) {
  statement(s);
}[/code]
A counter is declared once in [b]init[/b].
Next, the [b]condition [/b]evaluates the value of the counter and the body of the loop is executed if the condition is true.
After loop execution, the [b]increment [/b]statement updates the counter, also called the loop control variable.
The condition is again evaluated, and the loop body repeats, only stopping when the condition becomes [b]false[/b].
[b]For example: [/b][code format="cs" codeId="838"][b]for [/b](int x = 10; x < 15; x++)
{
  Console.WriteLine("Value of x: {0}", x);
}
/*
Value of x: 10
Value of x: 11
Value of x: 12
Value of x: 13
Value of x: 14
*/[/code]
[note]Note the [b]semicolons[/b] in the syntax.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print the EVEN values from 0 to 100 using a for loop:
[!raw!]
{0} (int x = 0; x < 100; x+={1})
{
  Console.WriteLine({2});
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The for Loop[/h1]

Compound arithmetic operators can be used to further control loop iterations. 
[b]For example: [/b][code format="cs" codeId="839"]for (int x = 0; x < 10; [b]x+=3[/b])
{
  Console.WriteLine(x);
}

/* Outputs
0
3
6
9
*/[/code]
You can also decrement the counter:[code format="cs" codeId="840"]for (int x = 10; x > 0; [b]x-=2[/b])
{
  Console.WriteLine(x);
}

/* Outputs
10
8
6
4
2*/[/code]

quizzes.question:
How many times will this loop run?
int x = 1;
for ( ; x < 7; )
{
  x+=2;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The for Loop[/h1]

The [b]init [/b]and [b]increment [/b]statements may be left out, if not needed, but remember that the semicolons are mandatory.
For example, the [b]init [/b]can be left out: [code format="cs" codeId="841"]int x = 10;
for ( ; x > 0; x -= 3)
{
  Console.WriteLine(x);
}[/code]
You can have the increment statement in the for loop body: [code format="cs" codeId="842"]int x = 10;
for ( ; x > 0 ; )
{
  Console.WriteLine(x);
  x -= 3;
}[/code]
[note][b]for (; ;) {}[/b] is an infinite loop.[/note]
